05:52.884 --> 05:56.087
People follow the crowd in
all kinds of interesting ways,

05:56.120 --> 05:58.524
many of which are pretty funny.

05:58.557 --> 06:00.725
Classical psychological experiments

06:00.759 --> 06:02.128
and hidden camera pranks

06:02.161 --> 06:05.598
often involve people acting
together in strange ways

06:05.630 --> 06:08.000
to see if others will conform.

06:08.033 --> 06:10.403
<i>Now, there's nothing
inherently irrational</i>

06:10.435 --> 06:13.004
<i>about following the
crowd in ways like those.</i>

06:13.038 --> 06:16.408
<i>Conforming can be a form
of social lubrication.</i>

06:16.442 --> 06:18.944
It's just easier to do
what someone else is doing,

06:18.976 --> 06:20.745
because to break from that norm

06:20.778 --> 06:22.615
would be to slow things down.

06:22.648 --> 06:25.850
<i>If everyone's facing the
same way in an elevator,</i>

06:25.884 --> 06:28.821
<i>it's not like you lose your
personal sense of identity</i>

06:28.853 --> 06:30.588
<i>by turning along with them.</i>

06:30.622 --> 06:32.925
<i>Instead, you're just
going with the flow</i>

06:32.958 --> 06:35.494
<i>and not being awkward.</i>

06:35.526 --> 06:38.029
<i>If I see a bunch of people
on the street looking up,</i>

06:38.062 --> 06:39.831
<i>and I decide to look up too,</i>

06:39.865 --> 06:41.834
<i>there's nothing
inherently bad about that.</i>

