and justification.</i>

12:05.123 --> 12:07.526
It's not a joke; I just made
that up, and it's nonsense.

12:07.558 --> 12:09.093
I know, that's why I
thought it was funny.

12:09.126 --> 12:10.094
'Cause it just would... make no sense?

12:10.128 --> 12:11.463
Yeah, that's why.

12:11.495 --> 12:12.831
I don't know. That's crazy, though,

12:12.864 --> 12:14.066
'cause it did make me laugh.

12:14.099 --> 12:16.001
[laughing]
- Everyone does that.

12:16.033 --> 12:17.503
- Yeah.
- It's typical human behavior...

12:17.535 --> 12:19.170
Yeah. It's true, though.

12:19.203 --> 12:21.873
To go with the flow and
to keep things moving.

12:21.907 --> 12:24.442
It's about just being
a good, social person.

12:24.475 --> 12:27.145
It's definitely a... a conformity thing.

12:27.178 --> 12:29.115
[laughter]

12:31.850 --> 12:36.321
One of the most disappointing
and terrifying aspects

12:36.354 --> 12:38.924
of our desire not to stand out

12:38.956 --> 12:40.958
is the bystander effect.

12:40.991 --> 12:44.096
People are less likely to help victims

12:44.129 --> 12:46.865
if other people are around.

12:46.898 --> 12:48.966
One of the most famous examples

12:49.000 --> 12:52.236
is told in Psych 101
classes all over the world.

12:52.269 --> 12:54.472
It's the story of Kitty Genovese,

12:54.505 --> 12:56.475
a woman who was brutally stabbed

12:56.508 --> 12:58.410
and raped in New York City

12:58.442 --> 13:00.578
in 1964.

13:00.611 --> 13:02.280
<i>It was a murder that symbolized</i>

13:02.313 --> 13:05.183
<i>the apathy of many
to big city crime.</i>

13:05.216 --> 13:08.220
<i>On a March night back in 1964,</i>

13:08.253 --> 13:10.989
<i>28-year-old bar
manager Kitty Genovese</i>

13:11.022 --> 13:12.891
<i>was stabbed to death on a street</i>

13:12.923 --> 13:14.492
<i>in Kew Gardens, Queens.</i>

13:14.525 --> 13:16.360
<i>Police say at least 38 people</i>

13:16.394 --> 13:17.495
<i>heard her screams</i>

13:17.528 --> 13:19.230
<i>but did nothing to help.</i>

13:19.264 --> 13:22.533
The hypothesis was that
each and every one of them

13:22.567 --> 13:24.970
<i>assumed someone else
would call the police,</i>

13:25.003 --> 13:28.040
<i>so they didn't have to
bother to do so themselves.</i>

13:28.072 --> 13:29.908
It wasn't their responsibility,

13:29.941 --> 13:32.978
so the police were never called.

13:33.010 --> 13:35.913
And Kitty died.

13:35.947 --> 13:38.082
<i> [somber music]</i>

13:38.115 --> 13:39.550
<i>But here's the thing:</i>

13:39.583 --> 13:41.919
<i>Kitty's story may
not be an example</i>

13:41.952 --> 13:43.889
of conformity,

13:43.922 --> 13:45.957
at least not in the
way we normally think,

13:45.990 --> 13:50.162
<i>because most of it
was totally untrue.</i>

13:50.195 --> 13:53.565
38 people didn't witness the attack.

13:53.597 --> 13:56.100
As it turns out, the
actual number of witnesses

13:56.134 --> 13:57.635
who could have helped and didn't

13:57.668 --> 14:00.438
may have been as few as two,

14:00.471 --> 14:03.140
<i>and people did call the police.</i>

14:03.173 --> 14:07.211
Samuel Hoffman spent three
or four minutes on hold

14:07.245 --> 14:10.381
before finally reaching
a police dispatcher.

14:10.414 --> 14:13.551
So where did the number 38 come from?

14:13.585 --> 14:16.054
<i>Well, it's theorized that
the police commissioner</i>

14:16.086 --> 14:17.923
<i>actually lied to a reporter</i>

14:17.956 --> 14:20.158
<i>about the number of
witnesses who did nothing</i>

14:20.191 --> 14:23.161
<i>in order to cover up why
the police took so long</i>

14:23.193 --> 14:25.197
<i>to arrive at the
scene of the crime.</i>

14:25.230 --> 14:28.267
<i>And the narrative of
uncaring New Yorkers</i>

14:28.299 --> 14:30.601
<i>turning a blind eye
to a woman's murder</i>

14:30.634 --> 14:32.203
<i>spread around the world,</i>

14:32.236 --> 14:34.238
<i>making front page headlines.</i>

14:34.272 --> 14:36.341
<i>As more and more sources</i>

14:36.374 --> 14:38.343
<i>repeated reports they'd heard,</i>

14:38.375 --> 14:41.279
<i>rather than going back
to investigate the truth,</i>

14:41.312 --> 14:43.048
a psychological phenomenon

14:43.081 --> 14:46.384
known as information cascade took place.

14:46.418 --> 14:49.053
<i>An information cascade develops</i>

14:49.086 --> 14:51.322
<i>when people have little
information themselves,</i>

14:51.355 --> 14:53.457
<i>so they depend on
inferences they can make</i>

14:53.490 --> 14:56.160
<i>based on earlier
people's actions.</i>

14:56.193 --> 15:00.097
So the conformity wasn't on
the part of the eyewitnesses.

15:00.130 --> 15:03.267
It was in the reporting of the story.

15:03.301 --> 15:05.137
There's a saying in journalism:

15:05.169 --> 15:08.240
"Some stories are too good to check."

15:14.178 --> 15:16.148
[projector whirring]

15:16.181 --> 15:18.150
<i>I'm going to give you this cup</i>

15:18.182 --> 15:21.086
that contains lysergic acid...

15:21.119 --> 15:23.322
100 micrograms.

15:23.355 --> 15:25.190
<i>Clinical trials:</i>

15:25.222 --> 15:27.591
<i>they can be enlightening,</i>

15:27.625 --> 15:28.592
<i>frightening,</i>

15:28.625 --> 15:30.294
<i>dangerous...</i>

15:30.327 --> 15:32.096
It seems to want to take
me over too much, you see,

15:32.129 --> 15:33.597
and I don't want to let myself go.

15:33.630 --> 15:36.168
<i>And also the perfect
high-stakes setting</i>

15:36.201 --> 15:38.269
<i>to test the power of conformity.</i>

15:41.373 --> 15:44.343
<i> [tense music]</i>

15:44.375 --> 15:46.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.577 --> 15:47.712
<i>This is Emma.</i>

15:49.380 --> 15:51.048
<i>She thinks she's taking part</i>

15:51.081 --> 15:52.183
<i>in a group study</i>

15:52.216 --> 15:53.284
<i>to measure the side effects</i>

15:53.317 --> 15:55.220
<i>of a new hallucinogenic drug.</i>

15:57.087 --> 15:59.423
So the drug that you are
helping us research today

15:59.456 --> 16:02.293
is NC-47.

16:02.326 --> 16:04.696
Today we're investigating
possible side effects.

16:04.729 --> 16:08.200
You know, there've been some
audio-visual distortions.

16:08.232 --> 16:11.369
You may see some images
behind your eyes...

16:11.403 --> 16:15.206
um, you know, some general
feelings of either calmness

16:15.240 --> 16:16.640
or euphoria.

16:16.673 --> 16:18.509
We're trying to examine
those a little further

16:18.543 --> 16:20.445
and find out a little bit more about how

16:20.477 --> 16:22.646
this drug is affecting everybody.

16:22.679 --> 16:24.750
<i>Emma is already looking
to the rest of the group</i>

16:24.783 --> 16:26.317
<i>for comfort.</i>

16:26.350 --> 16:27.753
Just take a cup, and just hang onto it.

16:27.785 --> 16:29.520
[whispering] Okay.

16:29.553 --> 16:31.523
<i>If everyone else is
participating willingly,</i>

16:31.556 --> 16:33.658
<i>it must be okay for her, too.</i>

16:33.691 --> 16:35.694
[laughter]

16:35.726 --> 16:37.095
We're all, like, scared to death.

16:37.128 --> 16:39.097
Okay.

16:39.129 --> 16:40.264
Go.

16:41.365 --> 16:45.803
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:45.836 --> 16:47.706
<i>But here's the catch:</i>

16:47.739 --> 16:50.709
<i>our subject didn't take a
hallucinogenic drug at all.</i>

16:50.741 --> 16:53.477
<i>It was simply a shot
of flavored water.</i>

16:53.510 --> 16:57.214
Just relax and concentrate.

16:57.248 --> 16:58.583
We'll give this just
a little bit of time

16:58.615 --> 17:00.317
to set in.

17:00.350 --> 17:02.620
<i>It doesn't take long
for our actors to feel</i>

17:02.653 --> 17:05.690
<i>the supposed side effects
of the so-called drug.</i>

17:05.722 --> 17:07.259
It's like a...

17:07.290 --> 17:09.226
like a line that goes across.

17:09.259 --> 17:11.229
It's almost like I'm looking
through a kaleidoscope,

17:11.261 --> 17:12.762
but it's, like, fuzzy.

17:12.797 --> 17:15.433
<i>Will our test subject
go along with the group?</i>

17:15.467 --> 17:17.602
<i>Or will she be bold
enough to stick out</i>

17:17.634 --> 17:19.237
<i>and say the truth?</i>

17:19.269 --> 17:22.441
It's like a... like a
lava lamp sort of thing.

17:22.473 --> 17:24.208
Hmm.

17:24.241 --> 17:25.409
Emma?

17:25.442 --> 17:26.609
Um, I honestly...

17:26.644 --> 17:28.246
I don't see anything. [laughs]

17:28.278 --> 17:30.182
- Mm.
- I don't see any shadows,

17:30.214 --> 17:31.649
shapes...

17:31.682 --> 17:33.518
I'm like, "Come on, I
want to see a shape."

17:33.550 --> 17:35.252
But I don't see anything, no.

17:35.286 --> 17:38.457
<i>Emma's honesty is
making her an outsider.</i>

17:38.490 --> 17:41.726
<i>Notice how she says she wants
to feel the side effects,</i>

17:41.759 --> 17:44.796
<i>which would enable her
to fit in with the group.</i>

17:44.828 --> 17:46.664
You can all sit down again.

17:48.333 --> 17:50.435
Okay, I want to do the audio test.

17:50.468 --> 17:51.803
We're just gonna go down the line,

17:51.836 --> 17:54.472
and I want you to just
say the word "hello."

17:54.506 --> 17:57.542
<i>Here's another opportunity
for Emma to conform.</i>

17:57.575 --> 17:59.344
<i>Will she go along with the group</i>

17:59.376 --> 18:02.246
<i>when she sees the actors
pretend to experience</i>

18:02.279 --> 18:05.716
<i>an auditory reaction
to the alleged drug?</i>

18:05.750 --> 18:07.551
Hello.

18:07.585 --> 18:08.553
Louder.

18:08.586 --> 18:10.889
Um, hello!

18:10.922 --> 18:12.723
And how did that feel?
What's your reaction?

18:12.757 --> 18:13.758
I hear, like, a delay.

18:13.790 --> 18:15.292
Like, um...

18:15.326 --> 18:16.560
Yeah, it could be called an echo.

18:16.594 --> 18:17.828
- It's more like
a... - Mm-hmm.

18:17.862 --> 18:19.798
Like a reverb or something.

18:19.830 --> 18:21.332
Yup, that's very common.

18:21.365 --> 18:23.134
All right, Ivory.

18:23.167 --> 18:25.803
Hello.

18:25.836 --> 18:28.606
Hello. [laughs]

18:28.640 --> 18:30.609
It's almost like, you know,
when you watch a video,

18:30.642 --> 18:32.811
and it's just like... just
the tiniest bit out of sync

18:32.844 --> 18:34.479
so you just barely notice it?

18:34.511 --> 18:37.448
Mm-hmm. All right, Emma?

18:39.450 --> 18:41.786
Hello.

18:41.818 --> 18:43.754
Hello?

18:45.890 --> 18:47.526
Hello.

18:47.558 --> 18:48.726
Yeah, it is echoing,

18:48.759 --> 18:49.861
like you had a shot...

18:49.894 --> 18:51.429
like you had a shot of vodka.

18:51.461 --> 18:53.265
- [laughing]
- Something like that, like...

18:53.298 --> 18:55.901
Yeah, acute audio
distortion is really common.

18:55.933 --> 18:58.737
- Okay.<i>
- Here we see a classic example</i>

18:58.769 --> 19:00.238
<i>of conformity.</i>

19:00.270 --> 19:01.906
<i>But is she just trying to fit in</i>

19:01.940 --> 19:04.176
<i>or does she truly believe</i>

19:04.209 --> 19:06.644
<i>she's experiencing
side effects now?</i>

19:06.678 --> 19:08.680
- I'm feeling pretty chill.
- Ivory?

19:08.712 --> 19:10.615
I feel kind of, like, just relaxed.

19:10.647 --> 19:12.449
I just feel, like, really relaxed.

19:12.482 --> 19:15.519
<i>She's now claiming to feel
multiple side effects.</i>

19:15.553 --> 19:16.821
But yeah, no, it's like I...

19:16.854 --> 19:18.456
I had, like, two drinks or something.

19:18.489 --> 19:20.192
Right, and in this moment now,

19:20.224 --> 19:21.425
how do you feel?

19:21.459 --> 19:23.228
- Uh, kind of tired.
- Tired.

19:23.260 --> 19:24.528
- Right?
- Yeah.

19:24.561 --> 19:25.896
- Am I the only one?
- No. [laughs]

19:25.930 --> 19:29.601
Should go, like, nap
on that bean bag, yeah.

19:29.634 --> 19:31.269
<i>Emma continues to
look to the group</i>

19:31.301 --> 19:32.836
<i>for reassurance
that her symptoms</i>

19:32.869 --> 19:34.405
<i>are in line with theirs.</i>

19:34.439 --> 19:35.473
I don't know if I like it.

19:35.506 --> 19:36.541
I can't decide.

19:36.574 --> 19:37.909
You know what I mean?

19:37.942 --> 19:39.510
What do you guys think? I don't know.

19:39.544 --> 19:41.278
<i>Whatever she thinks
she's feeling,</i>

19:41.311 --> 19:43.615
<i>she wants to make sure
it fits in with the group.</i>

19:43.647 --> 19:45.282
The room is warmer, no?

19:45.316 --> 19:46.918
Yeah.

19:46.951 --> 19:50.654
Would you take this while you
were operating a motor vehicle?

19:50.688 --> 19:52.290
No, I don't think so.

19:52.323 --> 19:54.492
Because...

19:54.525 --> 19:57.329
'Cause you need to concentrate
on what you're doing.

19:57.362 --> 19:59.631
But I just feel so relaxed.

19:59.663 --> 20:02.701
<i>Here we see an entirely
new level of conformity.</i>

20:02.733 --> 20:04.769
<i>Our subject is
actually experiencing</i>

20:04.801 --> 20:07.938
<i>physical manifestations
due to group pressure.</i>

20:07.971 --> 20:11.675
<i>Other subjects also
experienced physical sensations</i>

20:11.709 --> 20:13.979
<i>that they reported
in great detail.</i>

20:14.011 --> 20:15.813
Hello.

20:15.846 --> 20:18.383
I hear the echo. I can hear the echo.

20:18.415 --> 20:19.783
So you know an echo
would go out, then in?

20:19.817 --> 20:21.620
This is, like, just an in.

20:21.653 --> 20:22.787
I just feel, like, sensation,

20:22.819 --> 20:25.022
like, near my eye and nose area.

20:25.056 --> 20:26.725
I feel like it's definitely
getting brighter, though.

20:26.758 --> 20:29.760
Okay, could you say more
about the increased brightness?

20:29.794 --> 20:32.430
It's not comfortable to
look at the lights, really.

20:32.462 --> 20:34.398
<i>What we're seeing
from these subjects</i>

20:34.432 --> 20:36.768
<i>could be a form of
informational conformity,</i>

20:36.800 --> 20:38.035
<i>or even what's called</i>

20:38.068 --> 20:39.336
<i>a contact high,</i>

20:39.369 --> 20:40.604
<i>a psychological phenomenon</i>

20:40.637 --> 20:41.905
<i>that occurs when a sober person</i>

20:41.939 --> 20:43.775
<i>comes into contact with someone</i>

20:43.807 --> 20:45.609
<i>who is under the
influence of drugs</i>

20:45.643 --> 20:49.480
<i>and begins to manifest
the same physical symptoms.</i>

20:49.513 --> 20:50.914
I can now debrief you

20:50.948 --> 20:52.917
on what has been going on.

20:52.950 --> 20:55.553
So none of you took anything

20:55.586 --> 20:57.021
but, uh, water today.

20:57.055 --> 20:58.690
What?

20:58.722 --> 21:01.358
[laughter]

21:01.392 --> 21:03.595
And we're just kind
of looking at the way

21:03.627 --> 21:05.529
that groups conform together.

21:05.563 --> 21:07.599
We wanted to see what it would take

21:07.632 --> 21:09.968
to get someone to fall
in line with the group.

21:10.999 --> 21:12.304
Did you feel actual changes,

21:12.336 --> 21:13.438
or were you saying some things

21:13.471 --> 21:14.772
just to fit in and not stick out?

21:14.806 --> 21:16.408
No, I felt relaxed, so I don't get...

21:16.441 --> 21:17.976
I can't figure it...
I still feel relaxed.

21:18.009 --> 21:19.510
Are you surprised to have heard

21:19.544 --> 21:21.780
that you just drank water?

21:21.813 --> 21:22.914
Yeah.

21:22.946 --> 21:25.582
I definitely feel different.

21:25.615 --> 21:27.685
I actually did hear, yeah, an echo.

21:27.719 --> 21:30.622
<i>The desire to conform is so strong,</i>

21:30.654 --> 21:32.490
<i>the subjects continue to believe</i>

21:32.522 --> 21:34.391
<i>in their manifested symptoms,</i>

21:34.424 --> 21:36.627
<i>even after learning
the drug was fake.</i>

21:36.661 --> 21:38.563
I am prone to anxiety attacks, though,

21:38.596 --> 21:40.097
so I felt relaxed.

21:40.131 --> 21:42.334
Well, you should take
more of this nothing.

21:42.366 --> 21:44.302
[laughter]

21:47.105 --> 21:50.442
Human society is incredibly complex.

21:50.474 --> 21:53.811
<i>And the dueling forces
pushing us to conform</i>

21:53.845 --> 21:56.714
<i>and also to express our individuality</i>

21:56.748 --> 21:58.516
<i>are both necessary.</i>

21:58.548 --> 22:01.819
<i>Other people can
influence us in good ways</i>

22:01.853 --> 22:04.022
<i>and in not-so-good ways.</i>

22:04.055 --> 22:05.490
<i>But at the end of the day,</i>

22:05.522 --> 22:07.057
just remember this:

22:07.090 --> 22:10.061
what did the walrus say to the doctor?

22:11.596 --> 22:13.765
Give up?

22:13.798 --> 22:15.099
Cardboard.

22:15.133 --> 22:17.402
<i> [laughter]</i>

22:17.434 --> 22:19.403
Go ahead, laugh.

22:19.436 --> 22:21.105
Everyone's doing it.

22:21.138 --> 22:24.007
You don't want to look like
you don't get it, do you?

22:24.040 --> 22:25.643
Good, that's what I thought.

22:25.675 --> 22:26.977
Thanks for laughing,

22:27.010 --> 22:28.445
and as always,

22:28.479 --> 22:29.614
thanks for watching.

22:35.752 --> 22:38.722
<i> [electronic music]</i>

22:38.756 --> 22:45.697
<i>♪ ♪</i>
